title: For Sale/Trade:  spreewerk p38
postcontent:
very presentable spreewerk manufactured p38 9mm pistol . "cyq" as can be seen on the left side of the frame indicates this P.38 was manufactured at Spreewerke G.m.b.H. Metallwarenfabrik, Berlin, Germany. CYQ was simply the code the Germans used for that factory so that Allies could not target specific small arm factories (similar to "ac" for Walther and "byf" for Mauser)
all matching serial numbers, 'not a russian capture mixmaster', rather being an original wartime nazi issued pistol being used for post war police use. holster reads wunderlich berlin 1963. only issue being import marked very discreetly on the backstrap under the beavertail. 'very minute you wouldn't even notice' 
action is crisp tight, decocker works nicely nice shiny bore original magazine and one extra included, 

orvel L. Reichert who knew something about war time P-38s, produced a list that rates 1939 to 1953 P-38s from 1 to 10 based on how desirable they are. Most Spreewerk [cyq] have a letter after the serial number [ suffix }and are a 1. this p38 pistol has a letter [ a ] before the sn [ prefix] and rates a 3 as a 6th variation [a-b prefix]. The increased value of a prefix gun is also reflected on page 1434 of the 35 edition of BLUE BOOK OF GUN VALUES. The" CYQ late production second alphabet series" is about $300 more than a suffix.

reply by email call or text REDACTED

The Dual Beam Aiming Laser â Pistol (DBAL-PL) from Steiner is a multi-functional pistol aiming laser that can be attached to any handgun with an M1913 picatinny rail. 

It features four outputs: Infrared Laser Pointer + Infrared LED Illuminator and Visible Laser Pointer.

All IR functions are completely eye-safe / Class1.  Controls are easy and intuitive.  Two buttons are presented on an angled rearward-facing surfacing.  They are perfectly located for quick access and easily activated with or without gloves.  One button is marked âVISâ and activates the visible laser and 400 lumen white light at the same time.  The other button, marked âIR,â activates the infrared laser and infrared illuminator at the same time.  Both lasers are co-aligned to facilitate zeroing procedures.  Windage and Elevation adjustments require a small screw driver and are recessed to prevent accidental movement.  By zeroing one laser, you are zeroing the other in tandem. title: For Sale:  P-64 Polish Radom Pistol
postcontent:
I'm selling my Polish P-64 pistol, caliber 9X18mm Makarov.  It is in perfect condition, virtually unfired except for 24 rounds to verify reliability and accuracy.    The numbers all match, and it has a matching number on the magazine.  There is an extra magazine included.  The pistol was manufactured in 1968.  A small zipper carrying case is included with the gun.

THIS GUN IS NOT A MAKAROV. It does, however, use the 9x18mm, or, 9mm Makarov cartridge. The left side of the slide has factory rollmarks of 9mm  âP-64â.  Because the West knows the 9mm as the 9x19, importers added "Cal. Makarov" and "x18" in electropencil to indicate it's difference. The Polish P-64 and Makarov simply share their caliber - nothing else. 

The 9x18 will drive a 95gr bullet out the muzzle at around 1,000 FPS for about 231 ft. lbs. of energy far exceeding .22LR, .25 ACP or .32 ACP chambered pistols of similar size.

The right side of the slide is engraved with the Radom Circle 11 oval and shows the 1968 production date. 

The P-64 was designed during the late fifties by a team of Polish army officers.  Production started in the middle sixties under the official designation "9 mm pistolet wz. 1964" (9 mm pistol model 1964). 

The frame and slide are blued steel. The slide-mounted safety acts as a decocking lever and the slide can be operated when put on âSafeâ. Though it operates and looks similar to the Walther PP, there are some design differences between the P-64 and the PP/PPK pistols. Distinctly different from the PP/PPK design is a European-style magazine release located at the heel of the grip. The slide will lock back after the last shot has been fired but there is no slide lock lever. Instead, the magazine must be removed in order to close the slide when the gun is empty. Takedown, similar to other blowback pistols, is achieved by swinging the front of the trigger guard down and resting it against the frame, allowing the slide to come off of the front of the pistol. The fixed barrel can then be cleaned from the breach.

This would be a perfect pistol for concealed carry because of its size.  Makarov ammo is cheap and plentiful, and I'm throwing in a box of ammo just to get you started.  This would be the perfect Christmas gift for somebody special.  Contact me so we can meet and let you inspect this pistol.  I know you won't be disappointed.  The price is $275 Cash only, and you must show me your Oklahoma Driver's license.
